ight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."],[1043,"Bind address (default `127.0.0.1`)"],[519,"Bootstrap token"],[875,"Bot setup"],[1308,"Both operations require an admin-scoped token."],[584,"Browser session bootstrap (rate-limited)."],[520,"Browser sessions"],[271,"Budgets"],[290,"Budgets are hard stops, not advisories:"],[673,"Building agents on Runyard"],[1167,"Builds and pushes GHCR `hub` and `runner` container images behind the same two gates, and records both image digests as a release artifact."],[119,"By default a card is blocking: nothing happens until someone decides. Supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt` at creation makes it a **timed approval**:"],[334,"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."],[797,"Cancel; re-queue with same/edited input; merge a successful isolated run into its target branch"],[747,"Canonical"],[320,"Capacity and pool"],[272,"Capture paths: what is metered today"],[891,"Cards are posted to the configured chat with inline buttons (see below)."],[938,"Cards can deep-link into the Hub as a Telegram WebApp. `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp` exchanges the WebApp's signed init data for a browser session that is limited to the `approvals` scope — a Telegram identity can review and resolve approval cards, and nothing else. Full app access always requires a real access token."],[47,"Catalog"],[1131,"Catalog"],[1318,"Catalog grouping (for example `Examples`, `Operations`)."],[928,"Chat (group or DM) where approval cards are posted."],[1259,"Check run diagnostics; fix workflow config or runner setup."],[1147,"CI pipeline"],[374,"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."],[1027,"claims runs and executes them; workspace volume at `/workspace`"],[1251,"Class"],[590,"Clears the session cookie."],[886,"CLI"],[939,"CLI"],[1179,"CLI"],[868,"CLI guide — the same API from your terminal"],[34,"CLI:"],[285,"CLI: `runyard usage` (fleet rollup) and `runyard usage <runId>` (one run's detail)."],[1208,"Client install assets."],[930,"Comma-separated Telegram user ids allowed to resolve approvals."],[148,"Comment describes the requested changes."],[1248,"Common causes: the runner unit is idling because `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` is empty or revoked; the runner's tags do not include what the workflow requires (`requiredRunnerTags`, for example `smithers`); or the run asked for `--where local` and only `vps` runners are registered. Running `runyard preflight <workflow>` before enqueueing catches `no_matching_runner` up front."],[250,"Concepts"],[994,"Confidential VMs (dstack / Intel TDX)"],[1082,"Connect AI agents to a Runyard Hub with the runyard-mcp stdio server and its 87-tool surface."],[942,"Connecting to a Hub"],[254,"Control"],[1025,"control plane + web UI + embedded datastore (HTTP on `PORT`, default 8080 in-container)"],[207,"Copy verified artifacts to a configured target root (optionally with a public URL base)."],[301,"Coverage"],[836,"Create + preflight a draft: `{workflow, input, executionMode}` → `201` with status `ready` / `needs_input` / `blocked` and open questions"],[922,"Create a bot with Telegram's BotFather, then configure the Hub through en