[1012,"The repository ships a one-command, idempotent bootstrap script for a fresh\nLinux box:"],[1018,"The repository ships generic units in `deploy/`. The Hub unit\n(`deploy/runyard.service`):"],[21,"The repository's install script is a one-command, idempotent bootstrap. It installs Node 22 and pnpm if needed, clones Runyard at the latest release tag (default `/opt/runyard`), generates an env file with a `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` and session secret, creates the data directory, and installs systemd units for the Hub and a runner:"],[1224,"The reusable secret store is enabled by setting `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` (a 32-byte key) on the Hub; without a valid key the feature is disabled rather than degraded. Values are encrypted at rest and are write-only from the API's point of view: `GET /api/secrets` returns names and metadata, never values, and secrets are redacted from API responses, events, approval cards, and audit entries. Workflows reference secrets by name; the Hub injects values into runs that declared them."],[1264,"The run exceeded a deadline or an operation timed out."],[497,"the run input's `input.secretNames` list."],[902,"The run is cancelled — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."],[901,"The run is cancelled; your note tells the requester what to change."],[1249,"The run is held on an approval card, which is by design: approval-held runs are never failed or reaped for waiting. Find and resolve the card — web **Approvals**, `runyard approvals` then `runyard approve|reject|request-changes <approval-id>`, or the MCP tools. See Approvals."],[355,"The run lifecycle, preflight and run drafts, events and artifacts, reruns, and promotion."],[1017,"The runner authenticates with a runner-scoped token (`RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`); on a\nfresh Hub it may use the bootstrap token until you mint one."],[293,"The runner observes the terminal status on its next poll and cancels the detached engine run, and the gateway refuses further calls from that run's token (`403`)."],[353,"The runner protocol endpoints intentionally have no MCP tools — they are Hub↔runner machinery, not an operator surface."],[734,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle events and artifacts"],[535,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle, upload artifacts."],[1218,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle."],[1258,"The runner's preflight refused to execute (missing workflow source, auth not ready, repo path problems)."],[36,"The same data lives at `GET /api/runs/{id}`, `/api/runs/{id}/timeline`, `/api/runs/{id}/logs`, and `/api/runs/{id}/artifacts`, and in the web run page — the Hub is the source of truth even when execution happened on a local runner."],[531,"The same operating surface for MCP clients."],[1216,"The same operations over the MCP server."],[730,"The same operations, issued for MCP clients"],[23,"The script never prints secrets, never applies updates automatically, and prints a Caddy reverse-proxy snippet if you want TLS in front (recommended for anything non-local — see the security guide)."],[1098,"The server exposes **87 tools**, generated from the same API surface registry\nthe Hub's routes and `/openapi.json` come from. Grouped by resource:"],[1093,"The server name is `runyard` for the default remote and `runyard-<remote>` for\nothers, so one client can talk to several Hubs. &#x2A;*No token is stored in client\nconfigs.** At startup the server resolves its target in this order:"],[41,"The shared catalog of reusable agent roles, skills, and knowledge resources that workflows reference."],[186,"The shared catalogs (append `/:slug` for one entry)."],[226,"The side effect completed."],[914,"The side effect is skipped; the run's completed work is unaffected."],[913,"The side effect is skipped; your note explains what to change."],[228,"The side effect itself failed."],[1333,"The source is a small Smithers TSX workflow (modeled on the seeded `hello` workflow): one task, structured output validated with Zod."],[42,"The three catalogs"],[1097,"The token's scopes decide what the tools may do — a token with `mcp` scope can\ndiscover, preflight, and run workflows; `admin` unlocks the admin tools listed\nbelow."],[1139,"The tool list, the HTTP routes, and `/openapi.json` are all generated from one\nregistry, and a test fails the build when they drift: **every Hub API operation\nis either exposed as an MCP tool or carries a documented exemption** (exempt\noperations are browser pages, install assets, the runner-to-Hub machine\nprotocol, SSE streams that tools cover by polling, and legacy aliases). If you\ncan do it in the web UI or over HTTP, your agent can do it over MCP."],[1085,"The tool surface"],[715,"The typical flow"],[562,"The web app is an ordinary API client. `POST /api/auth/token-login` exchanges an access token for a **session cookie** — a signed copy of the token — so the browser session carries *exactly* the token's scopes, no extra power. Admin sections of the web app appear only for admin-scoped sessions. `POST /api/auth/logout` clears the cookie."],[698,"The web app is an ordinary client of the same HTTP API, with no privileged endpoints. Every route is declared in one registry that also generates `openapi.json` and is parity-tested against the MCP tool list — so a lossless third-party client is possible by construction: anything the web app can show or do, your client can too, over HTTP or MCP."],[286,"The web app: a usage chip on run cards, spent-vs-limit budget pairing on run detail, and fleet-wide totals in `GET /api/dashboard` (`stats.usage`)."],[1341,"The web app's workflow create/edit screens are ordinary clients of `POST /api/workflows` and `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`: they submit the definition with inline source bytes and the Hub publishes the bundle, exactly as above. There is no separate, privileged authoring path."],[1305,"The web editor"],[1273,"The workflow concluded a human must act."],[218,"The workflow must opt in via `workflow.hooks.allowedProfiles` (a list of profile slugs, or `\"*\"`); no opt-in means no hooks, default-closed."],[1330,"The workflow source bytes, sent inline as a string (aliases: `workflow.sourceBytes`, `workflow.code`)."],[496,"the workflow's declared `workflow.secrets` list, and"],[176,"The workflow's runs."],[1090,"Then let the CLI write your AI client's MCP config:"],[1036,"Then set `BASE_URL=https://hub.example.com` in the Hub's env file and restart.\nAn `https://` base URL switches the Hub into production session mode. If the\nproxy is not on loopback, set the trust-proxy configuration accordingly so\nclient IPs (used by rate limiting) are read from `X-Forwarded-For` only when\nthat header is trustworthy."],[981,"Then start the runner against the current remote (it inherits the remote's URL\nand token, or `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`):"],[20,"This page takes you from a fresh Linux box to a completed workflow run with logs and artifacts in the Hub."],[402,"Three ways to use it:"],[873,"Timed approvals and fallback"],[92,"Timed approvals with fallback"],[1092,"To configure a client by hand, print the snippet instead:"],[30,"To run an ad-hoc runner on any other machine (for example your laptop, for `local` execution):"],[692,"token"],[695,"token"],[569,"Token name and scopes."],[1119,"Tokens"],[515,"Tokens & Scopes"],[724,"Tokens are minted by an admin (web UI, `POST /api/tokens`, or the CLI) and carry\n**scopes**:"],[1210,"Tokens carry scopes; admins mint them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`."],[947,"Tokens, audit, and catalog"],[1100,"Tools"],[1137,"Tools marked † require an admin-scoped token."],[1154,"Trigger"],[213,"Trigger a preview deploy for a configured project."],[1235,"Troubleshooting"],[1185,"Trust boundary"],[1184,"Trust boundary, token scopes, secrets handling, runner sandboxing, and production posture for a Runyard deployment."],[980,"Turn a machine into a runner in three steps. First scaffold a workspace\n(requires `bun` and the `smithers` engine on `PATH`; it warns if no `claude`,\n`codex`, or `pi` agent CLI is found):"],[1209,"Two narrow exceptions authenticate by other means: `POST /api/telegram/webhook` is verified against the configured bot and webhook secret, and `POST /api/workflow-endpoints/{slug}` submissions authenticate with that endpoint's own secret (below). `GET /api/setup` returns only a reduced identity payload (instance name, auth mode) to unauthenticated callers."],[1276,"Unclassified failure."],[789,"Unified ascending timeline (`since=<iso>`, `limit=<n>`); backs `runyard tail`"],[1294,"Unified timeline: status transitions, events, artifacts as NDJSON."],[950,"Updating a host install"],[1303,"Updating a workflow"],[624,"Updating a workflow bumps its integer `version` and snapshots the previous definition. `GET /api/workflows/{name}/versions` lists the versions observed on past runs, and every run records the `workflowVersion` it executed. Bundle versions count separately, per publish."],[359,"Usage and budgets"],[298,"Usage is captured at the **inference boundary**, through two paths:"],[267,"Usage metering & budgets"],[269,"Usage records and the run aggregate"],[544,"Use for"],[114,"Values"],[923,"Variable"],[1038,"Variable"],[1059,"Variable"],[22,"Verify the Hub is up:"],[1287,"Verify, in order: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` and `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_CHAT_ID` are set on the Hub; the bot's webhook points at `https://hub.example.com/api/telegram/webhook` with the matching `TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET`; the bot is a member of the target chat; and the users pressing buttons are listed in `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_USER_IDS`. Response-endpoint deliveries record their state (`status`, `attempts`, `last_error`) on `GET /api/runs/{id}` under `responseEndpoints[]`."],[599,"Versioning"],[1145,"Versioning and releases"],[650,"Versions seen on runs."],[156,"View"],[172,"Visual graph tab."],[1262,"Wait and re-run; check the provider account."],[944,"Watch and manage runs"],[882,"Web app"],[33,"Web: open **Workflows**, pick &#x2A;*Hello (Smithers proof)**, fill in `topic`, and click Run."],[876,"Webhook"],[447,"What a fire produces"],[894,"What each decision does depends on the card's kind:"],[1,"What is Runyard"],[1155,"What it does"],[684,"What it gives you"],[48,"What it is"],[97,"What it represents"],[1290,"What it tells you"],[1192,"What stays out of public discovery docs"],[1316,"What the workflow does; shown in the catalog and menus."],[1253,"What to do"],[195,"When an agent hands off to a human — \"approve this\", \"read the logs\" — prefer relaying the payload's deep link over describing where to click."],[386,"When execution is interrupted by a condition a human can fix — the classic case is **the provider account ran out of credits** — the run parks as `paused` instead of failing. Pause metadata lives on `run.pause`:"],[1014,"When it finishes it prints next steps: sign in with the bootstrap token, mint a\nrunner-scoped token, put it in `/etc/runyard/runner.env`, and restart the runner\nunit."],[871,"Where approvals appear"],[997,"Where state lives"],[19,"Where to go next"],[1245,"Where to look, generally"],[278,"Where usage appears:"],[616,"Whether new runs hold for an approval before executing."],[1326,"Whether runs hold for a human approval before executing (`{ \"required\": true }`)."],[44,"Who can edit"],[1296,"Who did what (admin)."],[768,"With `\"negotiate\": true`, a non-ready request returns the negotiation state\n(questions, blockers, warnings, plus a saved draft) instead of creating a run —\nfix the input and call again."],[120,"With a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`), the configured decision is applied automatically when the timer elapses, recorded with `resolvedVia: \"fallback_timer\"`."],[741,"with status `403`. `GET /api/me` describes the calling token (name and scopes)."],[121,"Without a fallback, the elapsed card is flagged `fallback_required` and keeps waiting — no decision is invented, and the linked run is never failed by an elapsed timer."],[1127,"Workflow bundles"],[168,"Workflow catalog."],[170,"Workflow detail."],[1125,"Workflow endpoints"],[1188,"Workflow endpoints"],[600,"Workflow packages"],[946,"Workflow packages"],[1129,"Workflow packages"],[1138,"Workflow source is always created and edited **through these tools** —\n`create_workflow` / `update_workflow` take inline source bytes or an existing\n`workflow.bundleId`, and `import_workflow_package` installs a portable package\nas a disabled workflow. Bare file paths on the runner are rejected."],[621,"Workflow source is created and edited through the API/MCP (`create_workflow` / `update_workflow` with inline source bytes) or by importing a workflow package. You never write workflow files to disk on the Hub or runner: custom workflows must carry source bytes or reference an existing `workflow.bundleId` — bare `workflow.entry` file paths are rejected."],[597,"Workflow source is data, not files"],[777,"Workflow source, parsed metadata, sections, graph"],[594,"Workflows"],[1103,"Workflows"],[769,"Workflows and runs (`preflight` and `run` require `api` or `mcp` scope; reads\nrequire any token):"],[1306,"Workflows are stored in the Hub database as immutable, versioned source bundles. You create or update a workflow by sending its definition — **including the workflow source bytes** — over HTTP (`POST /api/workflows`, `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`) or MCP (`create_workflow` / `update_workflow`). The Hub publishes the source as a hash-addressed bundle and records its id on the definition as `workflow.bundleId`."],[817,"Workflows can pause on a human decision. Approval cards are first-class API\nobjects (resolving them requires `api`, `mcp`, or `approvals` scope):"],[977,"Workflows move between Hubs as portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package files\n— exported from one Hub and imported into another (admin token required).\nImported workflows arrive **disabled** for review before enabling; this is the\nsupported way to carry workflow source around, not files on a runner."],[1226,"Workflows whose consequences warrant a human get an `approvalPolicy` that holds runs in `waiting_approval` until someone approves; mid-run engine gates and gated side effects (post-run hook profiles are admin-defined and admin-configured) use the same approval cards. See Approvals."],[1066,"Workspace directory the runner executes workflows in"]],"type":"string"},"page_id":{"docs":{"1":0,"2":1,"3":2,"4":3,"5":4,"6":5,"7":6,"8":7,"9":8,"10":9,"11":1312,"12":1313,"13":1314,"14":1315,"15":1316,"16":1317,"17":1318,"18":1319,"19":1320,"20":1321,"21":1322,"22":1323,"23":1324,"24":1325,"25":1326,"26":1327,"27":1328,"28":1329,"29":1330,"30":1331,"31":1332,"32":1333,"33":1334,"34":1335,"35":1336,"36":1337,"37":1338,"38":1339,"39":1340,"40":27,"41":28,"42":29,"43":30,"44":31,"45":32,"46":33,"47":34,"48":35,"49":36,"50":37,"51":38,"52":39,"53":40,"54":41,"55":42,"56":43,"57":44,"58":45,"59":46,"60":47,"61":48,"62":49,"63":50,"64":51,"65":52,"66":53,"67":54,"68":55,"69":56,"70":57,"71":58,"72":59,"73":60,"74":61,"75":62,"76":63,"77":64,"78":65,"79":66,"80":67,"81":68,"82":69,"83":70,"84":71,"85":72,"86":73,"87":74,"88":75,"89":76,"90":77,"91":78,"92":79,"93":80,"94":81,"95":82,"96":83,"97":84,"98":85,"99":86,"100":87,"101":88,"102":89,"103":90,"104":91,"105":92,"106":93,"107":94,"108":95,"109":96,"110":97,"111":98,"112":99,"113":100,"114":101,"115":102,"116":103,"117":104,"118":105,"119":106,"120":107,"121":108,"122":109,"123":110,"124":111,"125":112,"126":113,"127":114,"128":115,"129":116,"130":117,"131":118,"132":119,"133":120,"134":121,"135":122,"136":123,"137":124,"138":125,"139":126,"140":127,"141":128,"142":129,"143":130,"144":131,"145":132,"146":133,"147":134,"148":135,"149":136,"150":137,"151":138,"152":139,"153":140,"154":141,"155":142,"156":143,"157":144,"158":145,"159":146,"160":147,"161":148,"162":149,"163":150,"164":151,"165":152,"166":153,"167":154,"168":155,"169":156,"170":157,"171":158,"172":159,"173"